                            <comment id="107387" author="olivergierke" created="Mon, 1 Sep 2014 03:30:08 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Property names with underscores are currently not supported as the underscore acts as a means to explicitly define property boundaries in case of ambiguities. Changing this entirely is not an option as it will inevitably break user code that is relying on the splitting behavior. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve got a fix locally that tries the original string if the resolution of the split value but I am a bit uncomfortable applying it to master as it basically only works in non-nesting scenarios. I.e. a scenario like &lt;tt&gt;shipping_address.zip_code&lt;/tt&gt; would still be not working.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What&apos;s the reason you&apos;re working with underscores in properties in the first place? If it&apos;s mapping to existing fields in MongoDB, is using &lt;tt&gt;@Field(&#8230;)&lt;/tt&gt; to customize the database field name an option maybe?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="116275" author="olivergierke" created="Wed, 3 Jun 2015 02:35:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think we&apos;re gonna change that to fixing the documentation rather that adding that feature as it would just lead to ambiguities in method names and very ugly method names in general. The general recommendation is to stick to Java coding style, i.e. use camel case for property names.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="116302" author="olivergierke" created="Thu, 4 Jun 2015 03:16:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve updated the reference documentation accordingly. See a preview of that &lt;a href=&quot;http://docs.spring.io/spring-data/commons/docs/1.11.x-SNAPSHOT/reference/html/#repositories.query-methods.query-property-expressions&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
